  "timeframe": "1H (entry); Monthly/Daily (bias)",
  "market_context": "Late October on USD/JPY. The monthly candle formed a candle 2 closure giving a bullish bias for October, with equal highs resting above as a draw on liquidity. The daily showed price wicking into a fair value gap and closing back above it at a point of interest.",
  "key_observation": "Monthly candle 2 closure plus daily fair value gap respect creates aligned bullish bias; the hourly can serve as the entry time frame without further refinement, looking for a continuation order block at equilibrium.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a candle 2 closure on the monthly timeframe, establishing a bullish bias for October on USD/JPY.",
    "Step 2: Noted equal highs resting above as a draw on liquidity, supporting continuation to the upside.",
    "Step 3: Dropped to the daily timeframe and confirmed price wicked into a fair value gap, with body respecting it and closing back above — a valid point of interest.",
    "Step 4: Used the hourly as the entry timeframe (fractal monthly→daily→hourly) instead of refining all the way down to 5-minute.",
    "Step 5: Looked for a continuation order block to form after open; required price to hold above equilibrium and not break below the prior structure.",
    "Step 6: Observed price reach into an hourly fair value gap, consolidate, make a new low, then close over the down-close candles forming a valid continuation order block.",
    "Step 7: Chose entry on retest (since highs were just taken, a retracement was likely) with stop on the full body of the continuation candles, targeting 2R."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade hit 2R target on the retest entry, confirming the monthly-to-daily-to-hourly bullish alignment played out.",
  "lessons": "Aligning monthly, daily, and hourly time frames in one direction at a valid point of interest produces high-probability expansion. The fractal model can use any three nested time frames; you do not always need to refine to the lowest LTF.",
